          "label": "<p>Which medullary nucleus is shared by cranial nerves IX and X for receiving both </p>",
          "x": 30,
          "y": 30,
          "width": 40,
          "height": 25,
          "libraryTitle": "Multiple Choice",
          "action": {
            "library": "H5P.MultiChoice 1.16",
            "params": {
              "question": "<p>Which medullary nucleus is shared by cranial nerves IX and X for receiving both taste and visceral sensory input?</p>",
              "answers": [
                {
                  "text": "<div>Nucleus ambiguus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The nucleus ambiguus provides motor fibres to pharyngeal and laryngeal muscles via CN IX, X, and XI. It is a motor nucleus, not a sensory relay for taste or visceral input.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Nucleus tractus solitarius</div>",
                  "correct": true,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>Correct! The NTS receives taste fibres (CN IX from the posterior tongue, CN X from the epiglottis) and visceral afferents (CN IX from the carotid body and sinus, CN X from thoracoabdominal organs).</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Dorsal nucleus of the vagus</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The dorsal nucleus of the vagus sends parasympathetic efferent fibres to thoracic and abdominal viscera. It is a motor (parasympathetic) nucleus, not a sensory relay.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                },
                {
                  "text": "<div>Spinal nucleus of the trigeminal nerve</div>",
                  "correct": false,
                  "tipsAndFeedback": {
                    "tip": "",
                    "chosenFeedback": "<div>The spinal nucleus of CN V receives somatic sensory fibres for pain and temperature from the face and ear — not taste or visceral sensation.</div>",
                    "notChosenFeedback": ""
                  }
                }
              ],
              "overallFeedback": [
                {
                  "from": 0,
                  "to": 50,
                  "feedback": "The nucleus tractus solitarius (NTS) is the correct answer. It is the convergence point for taste and visceral sensory input from both CN IX and CN X, making it functionally distinct from the motor nuclei (ambiguus, dorsal vagal, hypoglossal)."
                },
                {
                  "from": 51,
                  "to": 100,
                  "feedback": "Exactly right. The nucleus tractus solitarius is the key integrative sensory hub in the medulla, receiving both taste and visceral afferents from CN IX and X."
                }
              ],
